<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1910-08-19T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1910-08-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="661" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d661">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Ambassador <persName type="from">O’Brien</persName>
                                to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1910-08-19"><hi rend="italic">August 19,
                                1910</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>See memorandum with my 1160, May 10 last. Japanese Government unable to
                            reconcile additional protocol with their recommendation. Do you
                            understand that under it and independently of constitutional
                            difficulties Japan has the right to limit recourse against her in
                            international court to action for damages? Right of reservation seems
                            not to be general.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">O’Brien.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>